data.content:
Use EF Core 7+ **bulk operations** — `ExecuteUpdateAsync` and `ExecuteDeleteAsync`. They translate directly to SQL, bypassing the change tracker entirely:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Single UPDATE statement — no entities loaded
var cutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6);
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < cutoff)
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Single DELETE statement — no entities loaded
var logCutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1);
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Key differences from your original code:**

| | Original | Bulk |
|---|---|---|
| SQL | SELECT + N UPDATEs | 1 UPDATE / 1 DELETE |
| Memory | All entities loaded | Zero entities loaded |
| Change tracker | Involved | Bypassed |
| Round trips | Many | 1 |

**Caveats:**
- These **bypass the change tracker** — any already-tracked entities won't reflect the changes. Call `_db.ChangeTracker.Clear()` afterward if needed.
- No EF `SaveChanges` interceptors or events will fire.
- For the 2M-row delete, consider batching if your DB has lock escalation concerns:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```

Ensure `LastSoldDate` and `CreatedAt` columns are **indexed** for best performance.
